sec.p:
This study considers the EROI defined at the final energy stage1EROIfin=Gross energy producedEnergy invested=EoutEin.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \text{EROI}_\text{fin}&= \frac{\text{Gross energy produced}}{\text{Energy invested}} = \frac{{E}_\text{out}}{{E}_\text{in}}. \end{aligned}$$\end{document}Eout\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${E}_\text{out}$$\end{document} is computed at the final stage, i.e., the quantity of gasoline or electricity required by cars and trains, the heat produced for warming buildings, or the electricity delivered to households and companies. Ein\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${E}_\text{in}$$\end{document} is also measured in terms of final energy. It is composed of (1) the energy required for building and operating all the infrastructure of the energy system, from the cradle to the grave; (2) the energy used for operating the energy system.

The motivation of this definition is that energy enters the productive economy at the final energy stage. Figure 2 depicts the differences between primary energy production and final energy consumed with the concept of energy cascade. It illustrates the EROI of the system at the final stage. The numerator is the sum of all the types of final energy consumption considered in the system, such as electricity, heat, mobility, and non-energy. The denominator is the sum of all the indirect and direct energy invested for each step of the energy conversion from the primary energy production to the conversion and storage of the final energy into final energy consumption (FEC). Direct energy is required for the conversion energy process, such as the energy to extract and produce gas and oil in the field. Indirect energy is related to the products used at each step of the conversion process, such as the infrastructure used to extract and produce gas and oil in the field. Note that the FEC definition adopted in this study is provided by European Commission—Eurostat (2022): it excludes energy used by the energy sector, including distribution and transformation, and it is the energy that reaches the final consumer’s door, such as households or industries. Therefore, EROIfin\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\text{EROI}_\text{fin}$$\end{document} defined in Eq. (1) corresponds to the net external energy return (NEER) from the nomenclature of Brandt and Dale (2011).Fig. 2
The energy cascade illustrates the EROI of the system at the final stage (EROIfin\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\text{EROI}_\text{fin}$$\end{document}), considered in this study, with the direct and indirect energy invested at each step of the energy conversion required to produce final energy and satisfy the final energy consumption. This figure was adapted from Brockway et al. (2019)

In this study, the objective function is modified to maximize EROIfin\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\text{EROI}_\text{fin}$$\end{document} instead of minimizing the total cost of the system. The model uses fixed EUD as input parameters where the EUD is related to the numerator in the EROIfin\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\text{EROI}_\text{fin}$$\end{document} definition Eq. (1). Maximizing the EROI of the whole-energy system is similar to maximizing the ratio between the energy services, expressed in this work in terms of EUD and the quantity of energy invested. Since the same EUD is considered for each simulation, we only minimize the denominator: the energy invested Ein\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${E}_\text{in}$$\end{document}. In practice, EROIfin\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\text{EROI}_\text{fin}$$\end{document} Eq. (1) is computed ex-post by using the optimization result with 2aEout=FEC,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} {E}_\text{out}&= \text{FEC}, \end{aligned}$$\end{document}2bEin=argminEin,tot,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} {E}_\text{in}&= \arg \min \mathbf{E}_\text{in,tot}, \end{aligned}$$\end{document} where the final energy consumption (FEC) is derived from the simulation result with the methodology detailed in Appendix 2.

Thus, the model optimizes the design and the operational strategies to minimize the total annual system energy invested Ein,tot\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
